The paper is about multi-objective reinforcement learning, which is a subfield of machine learning. The proposed approach is policy-based and exploits gradient information, which suggests that it belongs to the sub-category of "cs.LG" (Machine Learning). The paper also deals with Markov Decision Problems, which is a common topic in the sub-category of "cs.AI" (Artificial Intelligence). The approach is evaluated empirically, which suggests that it belongs to the sub-category of "cs.RO" (Robotics). The paper also discusses the issue of defining a metric to assess the quality of the candidate Pareto frontiers, which suggests that it belongs to the sub-category of "cs.SY" (Systems and Control). Finally, the paper proposes a novel approach to multi-objective optimization, which suggests that it belongs to the sub-category of "cs.DS" (Data Structures and Algorithms).
